The paper discusses the use of Artificial Immune Systems (AIS) as a metaphor for agent-based modeling of crisis response operations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) as AIS is a subfield of AI. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of multi-agent systems, situation management, and learning, which are all relevant to the sub-category of Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA). The paper also discusses the use of defensive models, which is relevant to the sub-category of Security and Cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the application of the proposed model to the spread of pandemic influenza, which is relevant to the sub-category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) as it involves the interaction between humans and technology. Finally, the paper discusses the use of intensity-based learning, which is relevant to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) as it involves the analysis of data and information.
